<br>
...these are the same quality of people that are engaging in other phone related service activites...<br>
<br>
...like... oh... you know... alarm monitoring companies and such.<br>
<br>
I worked at this one company which shall go nameless.  A guy lived in a county where you were required to have an alarm permit for the fire department to respond to a fire alarm at your house (vs you being there and calling 9-1-1).<br>
<br>
He wasn't home, and his fire alarm went off.  The monitoring guy called the fire dept, it went something like this...<br>
<br>
[Guy] Hi... um... we have a house that has a fire alarm going off.<br>
<br>
[Fire Dept] Can I have the permit number?<br>
<br>
[Guy] A what?<br>
<br>
[Fire dept] A permit number is required for us to respond to a fire alarm.  Does the homeowner have a permit.<br>
<br>
[Guy] Ummmm.... no, I don't think so.<br>
<br>
[Fire dept] I'm sorry sir, than we can't respond.<br>
<br>
[Guy] Oh... okay.  /hangs up.<br>
<br>
That's all the action he took.  Didn't try to contact the home owner or any of the emergency contacts or anything.  Just moved on to his next call.<br>
<br>
Kicker is... the homeowner <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>had a permit</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->!  It was right there on the account screen, the moron operator guy just didn't read it.<br>
<br>
Lucky for the homeowner it was just some food burning in the kitchen that set off the alarm.  He called us out of curiosity why his fire alarm went off but no one responded is why we were even aware of it.<br>
